Defines how sub-criteria relate to their parent criterion.
Additional Information: Examples:
1) Inheritance: in eProcurement for example, the Exclusion and Selection Criteria established in the Directives are "parents" of possible
2) Dimensions: In different business domains criteria of first order are used to group sub-criteria of second order (break-down); e.g. different domains that measure different dimensions are: - Procurement: Price, Cost, Quality - Software Product: Price, User-friendliness, Easy installation, Maintenance Assurance, etc. - Military staff selection: Aptitudes, Motivation, Personality, Physical Condition, etc.

properties.documentation:
Individual ResponseValues are supported with Assets subclassed as Evidences. This allows TOOP to not use Criterion and nonetheless use the cccev:Evidence, because it is a subclass of Asset.
Asset can be used thus as an interface pointing to any type of artefact or device providing any type of object.
